Exercise 3.6
Two problems involving two norms. Let $A \in \mathbf{R}^{m \times n}$ and $b \in \mathbf{R}^m$ be given, and let the variable be $x \in \mathbf{R}^n$. Consider the optimization problem

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \dfrac{\|Ax-b\|_1}{1-\|x\|_\infty} \\
\mbox{subject to} & \|x\|_\infty<1,
\end{array}
\tag{1}
\]

and the closely related problem

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \dfrac{\|Ax-b\|_1^2}{1-\|x\|_\infty} \\
\mbox{subject to} & \|x\|_\infty<1.
\end{array}
\tag{2}
\]

Assume $b \notin \mathcal{R}(A)$, so that $\|Ax-b\|_1>0$ for all $x$, and hence the strict constraint $\|x\|_\infty<1$ may equivalently be replaced by $\|x\|_\infty\leq 1$ if desired.

Answer the following question for each of the two problems (so there are two separate answers, one for (1) and one for (2)):

(a) Is the problem, exactly as stated and for arbitrary problem data $A,b$, a convex optimization problem? If not, is it quasiconvex? Justify your answer.

Exercise 4.10
Binary least-squares. We consider the nonconvex least-squares approximation problem with binary constraints

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \|Ax-b\|_2^2 \\
\mbox{subject to} & x_k^2 = 1,\quad k=1,\ldots,n,
\end{array}
\tag{10}
\]

where $A\in \mathbf{R}^{m\times n}$, $b\in \mathbf{R}^m$, and $x\in \mathbf{R}^n$. We assume that $\operatorname{rank}(A)=n$, i.e., $A^T A$ is nonsingular.

One possible application of this problem is as follows. A signal $\hat{x}\in \{-1,1\}^n$ is sent over a noisy channel, and received as $b=A\hat{x}+v$ where $v\sim \mathcal{N}(0,\sigma^2 I)$ is Gaussian noise. The solution of (10) is the maximum likelihood estimate of the input signal $\hat{x}$, based on the received signal $b$.

Let (11) denote the SDP relaxation of (10):

\[
\begin{array}{ll}
\mbox{minimize} & \operatorname{tr}(A^TAZ)-2b^TAz+b^Tb \\
\mbox{subject to} & Z_{ii}=1,\quad i=1,\ldots,n,\\
& \left[\begin{array}{cc}
Z & z\\
z^T & 1
\end{array}\right] \succeq 0,
\end{array}
\tag{11}
\]

with variables $Z\in \mathbf{S}^n$ and $z\in \mathbf{R}^n$.

(d) Solve the SDP problem (11) using CVX. Generate problem instances using the Matlab code

\begin{verbatim}
randn('state',0)
m = 50;
n = 40;
A = randn(m,n);
xhat = sign(randn(n,1));
b = A*xhat + s*randn(m,1);
\end{verbatim}

for four values of the noise level $s$: $s = 0.5$, $s = 1$, $s = 2$, $s = 3$. For each problem instance, compute suboptimal feasible solutions $x\in\{-1,1\}^n$ using the following heuristics and compare the results.

(i) $x^{(a)} = \operatorname{sign}(x_{\mathrm{ls}})$ where $x_{\mathrm{ls}}$ is the solution of the least-squares problem

\[
\text{minimize} \quad \|Ax - b\|_2^2,
\]

over $x\in\mathbf{R}^n$.

(ii) $x^{(b)} = \operatorname{sign}(z)$ where $z$ is the optimal value of the variable $z$ in the SDP (11).

(iii) $x^{(c)}$ is computed from a rank-one approximation of the optimal solution $(Z,z)$ of (11).

(iv) $x^{(d)}$ is computed by rounding 100 samples from the Gaussian distribution $\mathcal{N}(z,\, Z-zz^T)$, where $(Z,z)$ is the optimal solution of (11).
